[[File:Staurogram.svg|thumb|upright=0.5|The Staurogram, also called the Tau-Rho, and the Monogrammatic cross.]] [[File:P. Bodmer XIV-XV, staurogram.jpg|thumb|A staurogram used as τρ-ligature part of the spelling of the word ''σταυρον'' (as {{overline|Ϲ⳨ΟΝ}}) in [https://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=Luke+14:27 Luke 14:27] ([[Papyrus 75|Papyrus Bodmer XIV]], 2nd century).]] [[File:Solidus Anastasius.jpg|thumb|A [[Solidus (coin)|solidus]] minted under [[Anastasius I Dicorus]] (struck in Constantinople between 507–518). On the obverse is [[Nike (mythology)|Victory]] standing left, holding a staff surmounted by a staurogram.]] [[File:Nahsholim-Tel-Dor-3187.jpg|thumb|An [[Early Christian lamps|oil lamp]] with staurogram from [[Caesarea Maritima]]. Glass Factory Museum, [[Nahsholim]], Israel.]]
The '''staurogram''' ('''⳨'''), also '''monogrammatic cross''' or '''''tau-rho''''',<ref>The term ''[[:wikt:staurogram|staurogram]]'' in this sense is of relatively late coinage (1960s); "monogrammatic cross" is in use in the later 19th century.</ref> is a [[typographic ligature|ligature]] composed of a superposition of the letters [[tau (letter)|tau]] ('''Τ''') and [[rho (letter)|rho]] ('''Ρ''').
==Overview== The staurogram was first used to abbreviate ''[[stauros]]'' ({{lang|grc|[[wiktionary:σταυρός|σταυρός]]}}), the Greek word for [[Christian cross|cross]] in very early [[New Testament manuscripts]] such as [[Papyrus 66|P66]], [[Papyrus 45|P45]] and [[Papyrus 75|P75]], almost like a [[nomina sacra|nomen sacrum]], and may visually have represented [[Crucifix|Jesus on the cross]].<ref name="Hurtado">{{cite book | editor-last = Kraus | editor-first = Thomas | title = New Testament Manuscripts | publisher = Brill | location = Leiden | year = 2006 | isbn = 978-90-04-14945-8 | chapter=The Staurogram in Early Christian Manuscripts: the earliest visual reference to the crucified Jesus? | first=Larry| last=Hurtado| authorlink=Larry W. Hurtado | pages=207–26 |url=http://hdl.handle.net/1842/1204}}</ref>
The Tau-Rho as a [[Christian symbol]] outside its function as [[nomen sacrum]] in biblical manuscripts appears from c. the 4th century, used as a ''[[Christogram|monogramma Christi]]'' alongside the [[Chi-Rho]] and other variants, spreading to Western Europe in the 5th and 6th centuries.<ref>{{cite book | last = Redknap | first = Mark | title = The Christian Celts: treasures of late Celtic Wales | publisher = National Museum of Wales | location = Cardiff | year = 1991 | isbn = 978-0-7200-0354-3 |page=61}}</ref>
[[Ephrem the Syrian]] (4th century) discusses a Christian symbol, apparently combining the Tau-Rho with [[Alpha and Omega]] placed under the left and right horizontal arms of the Tau. Ephrem says that the Tau represents the cross of Jesus (prefigured by the outstretched hands of [[Moses]] in {{bibleverse||Exodus|17:11|KJV}}), the Alpha and Omega signify that the crucified Christ is "the beginning and end", and the Rho, finally, signifies "Help" ({{lang|grc|βοήθια}} {{sic}}; classical spelling: {{lang|grc|[[:wikt:βοήθεια|βοήθεια]]}}), because of the [[Numerology|numerological]] value of the Greek word being [[100 (number)|100]], represented by Rho as a [[Greek numeral]].<ref>Hurtado (2006), citing [[Franz Joseph Dölger|F. J. Dölger]], ''Sol Salutis'' (1920), [https://fedora.phaidra.univie.ac.at/fedora/get/o:34206/bdef:Book/view# p. 61] (note 2).<!--sic, p. 61 in the original (1920) edition, Hurtado cites p. 74 from a later (1925?) edition. Dölger's footnote cites the Greek text from the 1746 edition of Ephraem's text.--> ''Ephraem in sanctam Parasceven'', ''Ephraem Syri opera omnia quae extant graece — syriace — latine'' Tom. III Romae 1746, p. 477. </ref>
The two letters tau and rho can be found separately (not in ligature) as symbols already on [[early Christianity|early Christian]] [[ossuaries]].<ref name="Bagatti"/> [[Tertullian]] (''Contra Marcionem'' 3.22) explains the Tau as a symbol of salvation by identification with the sign which in {{bibleverse||Ezekiel|9:4|KJV}} was marked on the forehead of the saved ones.<ref name="Hurtado"/> The rho by itself can refer to Christ as [[Messiah]] because [[Abraham]], taken as symbol of the Messiah, generated [[Isaac]] according to a promise made by God when he was one hundred years old, and 100 is the value of rho.<ref name="Bagatti">[[Bellarmino Bagatti|Bagatti, Bellarmino]], "The Church from the Circumcision: history and archaeology of the Judaeo-Christians", ''Studium Biblicum Franciscanum'', Collectio Minor n. 2, Jerusalem (1984). </ref>{{rp|158}}
The staurogram is encoded by [[Unicode]] in the [[Coptic (Unicode block)|Coptic]] block, at {{unichar|2CE8|Coptic Symbol Tau Ro}}, and as of Unicode 7.0 (2014) also in the [[Ancient Symbols]] block, at {{unichar| 101A0|greek symbol tau rho}}. The Coptic block has a ligature of the full word σταυρός, where the τρ is represented by the staurogram, and two [[lunate sigma]]s are attached to either side of the tau's horizontal bar, at {{unichar|2CE7|Coptic symbol Stauros}}.
